ents,\" which suggests the real failure mode emerges from how actual reviewers produce conflicts—pushing confidence to Agentic at 0.85. Merging logic must handle the specific conflicts real reviewers generate, not just theoretical ones.\n\nFor Behavior 5, the full pipeline orchestrates three real reviewers and merges their outputs, making this explicitly a Workflow-level concern at 0.82 confidence. The test descriptions should capture these distinctions—starting with the clause extractor on real contracts for Behavior 1.\n\nVerify that key terms like parties, dates, obligations, and penalties are identified across contracts with varying complexity and language styles. The extractor must handle diverse phrasing conventions. This is plan_consistent because the real LLM-based extractor needs to run—mocking would mask extraction failures.\n\nFor Behavior 2, the risk assessor must detect both direct and indirect risk language, including euphemisms like \"unfavorable conditions\" masking contract breaches. Testing across multiple risk policies ensures correct application. This is plan_consistent since the real LLM-based assessor must run to verify semantic understanding—mocking would hide how it handles nuanced language.\n\nFor Behavior 3, run the compliance checker against real contracts with known compliance status across the configured jurisdiction. Test clearly compliant cases, clearly non-compliant cases, and edge cases near regulatory boundaries. This is plan_consistent because the real compliance checker must run to verify regulatory knowledge.\n\nFor Behavior 4, run the clause extractor and risk assessor on the same contract clause and verify that when they produce conflicting assessments—such as the extractor identifying a \"standard clause\" while the risk assessor flags it as \"high risk\"—both assessments are preserved with correct source attribution. Test across multiple contracts to ensure conflicts are naturally generated and handled correctly. This is most