nts. So behavior 4 should weight toward Agentic (0.70) while behavior 5 should weight toward Workflow. sense. Behavior 4 tests a subset of the system—two reviewers with merge logic—making it primarily Agentic (0.70) with meaningful Workflow contribution (0.19) since orchestration across multiple components is involved. Behavior 5 exercises the complete end-to-end pipeline with all three reviewers, pushing it firmly into Workflow territory (0.82) with some Agentic elements (0.15) for the individual agent interactions. The probability distributions reflect this: behaviors 1-3 stay concentrated in Agentic space, behavior 4 shifts toward Workflow, and behavior 5 is dominated by Workflow-level concerns.\n\nVerifying the distributions sum correctly: each row totals 1.00 across all five categories. Now for the justifications—behavior 1 requires running the actual clause extractor against real legal contracts to catch when the model fails to identify key terms like parties, dates, obligations, and penalties. Mocking responses would mask the real extraction quality, so this demands Agentic-level testing with genuine legal documents.\n\nFor behavior 2, detecting euphemistic or indirect risk language depends on the model's actual semantic understanding. Testing against real contract text with realistic risk scenarios reveals whether the risk assessor truly catches subtle policy violations that mocking would always pass.\n\nFor behavior 3, compliance checking requires the real model's knowledge of jurisdiction-specific regulations and its ability to match contract language against those requirements. Mocking would obscure whether the model actually understands regulatory nuances or simply appears to.\n\nThe test should run the compliance checker against contracts with established compliance status across multiple jurisdictions, verifying that clearly compliant contracts pass, clearly non-compliant ones fail, and edge cases near regulatory boundaries are handled appropriately. Ground truth labels from legal experts provide validation.\n\nFor behavior 4, when two reviewers produce conflicting assessments of the same clause—such as the extractor marking it \"standard\" while the risk assessor flags it \"high risk\"—the merge step must preserve both assessments with proper attribution. Testing this with actual reviewer outputs is essential because real reviewers generate natural disagreements on realistic contracts, the merge logic must handle the specific format and content of real LLM outputs, and mocking would miss unexpected scenarios where reviewers genuinely conflict. The test should run both the clause extractor and risk assessor on 10+ contracts, identifying conflicts and verifying that both assessments are preserved, correctly attributed to their source, and nothing is dropped or modified. If natural conflicts don't emerge frequently enough, contracts can be designed with ambiguous language or policy edge cases to trigger disagreement.\n\nThe full pipeline—dispatching all three reviewers in parallel, collecting their results, and merging into a unified report—must complete without losing any findings. Running the extractor, risk assessor, and compliance checker together on 5–10 real contracts will expose orchestration failures like lost outputs during collection, silent discarding of findings, or race conditions from parallel execution.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13477,"cache_read_input_tokens":33379,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13477},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"92b856e7-833b-489c-b7d6-a8de68bb5af5","uuid":"25b65600-07e2-4c93-a3c1-3389f5f93e41"}
